<DOC><DOCNO> AP880829-0029 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-88 0118EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Missiles     08-29 0284</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Soviet-Missiles,0292</SECOND><HEAD>Soviets Begin Destruction of SS-20 Nuclear Missiles</HEAD><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Soviet Union has begun destroying its SS-20missiles in line with the U.S.-Soviet pact to eliminate thesuperpowers' intermediate-range nuclear forces, according to Tass.   It said three of the multiple-warhead SS-20s were blown upSunday as part of the compliance with steps outlined in theIntermediate-Range Nuclear Forces treaty. Under the accord, the twosuperpowers are to get rid of all of their nuclear weapons thathave ranges of between 300 and 3,400 miles.   Tass said Sunday's demolition occurred at the same locationwhere the SS-20s were tested _ at the Kapustin Yar site 600 milessoutheast of Moscow.   The official news agency said representatives of the 40-nationU.N. Conference on Disarmament observed the destruction of themissiles.   About 600 SS-20s are to be destroyed at Kapustin Yar in batchesof three or more on the 15th and 30th of each month for the nextthree years, Tass said.   It said that on Thursday, two SS-20s were destroyed by launchingin the Siberian area of Chita amid pine and fir trees.   One SS-20 was blown up July 22 at Kapustin Yar. Americaninspectors insisted that the missile be dismantled so they couldcheck the dimensions of its stages, and it then was blown upbecause it was dangerous in the dismantled state, according to Tass.   Overall the treaty requires the United States to scrap 867medium-range nuclear-capable missiles and the Soviet Union todestroy 1,752.   The first U.S. weapons destruction under the treaty is scheduledto begin Sept. 8 when solid-fuel rocket motors for Pershing IImissiles are to be destroyed at the Longhorn Army Ammunitions plantnear Marshall, Texas.</TEXT></DOC>